Data Pre-Processing

This section describes the pre processing phase of the data set for further analysis

To have a better understanding of the data set, we will process the existing product sales data as follows;

    1. Get the weighted mean of the customer star reviews,
    1. Group the product types into their respective fields for deeper analysis
    1. Remove variables or fields that are of less importance to the prediction of volume sales. In this case, the rationale behind removing 5,3 and 1 star reviews is that it has less significance when predicting volume.
#make a copy of the data
existingSalesEDA <- copy(existing_product)

# Remove column with NA values "BestsellerRanks"
existingSalesEDA$BestSellersRank <- NULL

#Get the weighted mean of the Star reviews
existingSalesEDATrans <- existingSalesEDA %>%
 mutate(
  OverallStarReview = round((x5StarReviews*5 + x4StarReviews*4 + x3StarReviews*3 + x2StarReviews*2 + x1StarReviews*1) / (x5StarReviews + x4StarReviews + x3StarReviews + x2StarReviews + x1StarReviews),digits = 1),
  .after = x1StarReviews
 ) %>% 
  select(-x5StarReviews, -x3StarReviews, -x1StarReviews)

existingSalesEDA$OverallStarReview <- existingSalesEDATrans$OverallStarReview
# copy data for correlation analysis


# Dummify Sales by creating  variable for each product type
dummyfiedData <- dummyVars('~.', data = existingSalesEDATrans)

existingSalesEDATransDummified <- data.frame(predict(dummyfiedData, newdata = existingSalesEDATrans))


# define and plot a correlation matrix
correlationData <- copy(existingSalesEDA)
correlationData$ProductType <-NULL
correlationData$ProductNum  <-NULL

corrold <- cor(correlationData)
corrDataDummy <- cor(existingSalesEDATransDummified)

#png(filename = "corrplot.png", width = 1200, height = 800)
corrplot(corrDataDummy,method = 'number',addCoef.col = 1,number.cex = 0.4, tl.cex = 0.4, title = 'orrelation Matrix of existingSalesEDA')

corrplot(corrold,method = 'number',addCoef.col = 1,number.cex = 0.4, tl.cex = 0.4, title='Correlation Matrix of existing_product')

new_product<-read.csv("newproductattributes2017.csv")

# Remove column with NA values "BestsellerRanks"
new_product$BestSellersRank <- NULL

#Get the weighted mean of the Star reviews
new_productsTrans <- new_product %>%
 mutate(
  OverallStarReview = round((x5StarReviews*5 + x4StarReviews*4 + x3StarReviews*3 + x2StarReviews*2 + x1StarReviews*1) / (x5StarReviews + x4StarReviews + x3StarReviews + x2StarReviews + x1StarReviews),digits = 1),
  .after = x1StarReviews
 ) %>%
  select(-x5StarReviews, -x3StarReviews, -x1StarReviews)

# Dummify Sales by creating  variable for each product type

Removing Outliers in Volume

The data distribution of the volume shows the presence of two outliers that could be impact the prediction of volume of sales.

In order to minimize the chances of wrong prediction of volumes , it is important we eliminate any disturbances to the distribution of the target variables by removing the two outliers in the data set.

INSIGHTS:

  • The distribution of volume against the product type shows the number of sales per product. We can see that Game console more than the rest of the product types. We could also spot some extreme sales volume in is one or two types of accessories.

  • The distribution of price and volume shows a cluster in the region of 0 to 500 dollars and 0 to 2600 sales volume.

  • In both the 4 and 2 star reviews, we can see a general trend. Thus the higher the volume purchased the more the review counts in the respective stars

  • The overall star Review shows some different trends among the product types, for the majority, the higher the volume od sales, the more the review tends to 5 star. For Pc, software, tablet and laptops we see a downward trend the more the volume the less reviews it gets. this is a major cause of concern.

  • The distribution of the positive and negative service reviews show that in the majority of the product types, the more the volume of sales, the more likely a product will have more positive and negative reviews. This is ideal and expected.

  • The shipping weight distribution with volume of sales and product type tells us that Accessories, GameConsoles, Printers and Printersupplies all have a similar trend that says the higher the volume the less the shipping weight. Majority of the product types shows that the higher the volume the more the shipping weights. # Modeling

The modeling phase describes the process of modeling our sales data

Feature Selection and Engineering

After a careful observation of the training data set, we observed that the following variables have no values that could be compared and eventually not contributing to prediction of the target variable Volume or they are in significant to predicting the volume of sales. This is due to one of the limitations of data set few records where given.

The feature selection process helps to determine the importance of the variables that will be used in predicting the volumes of sales of products

Every other features or variables aside the following given below will be used in predicting the volume based on the absence of values to compare during the modeling.

#existingSalesOutliersRemoved
# Remove variables with no values to compare in the training set. 
existingSalesOutliersRemoved$ProductNum <- NULL
existingSalesOutliersRemoved$ProductTypeGameConsole <- NULL
existingSalesOutliersRemoved$ProductTypePrinterSupplies <- NULL
existingSalesOutliersRemoved$ProductTypeDisplay <- NULL

#splittingDataSet

#Setting seed
set.seed(234)

# Splitting data set into train and test
index <- createDataPartition(existingSalesOutliersRemoved$Volume, p = 0.70, list = FALSE)
trainSet <- existingSalesOutliersRemoved[index, ]
testSet <- existingSalesOutliersRemoved[-index, ]

fitControl <- trainControl(method = "repeatedcv", number = 5, repeats =3)

Training Models

Training data set with KNN Model

set.seed(167)
tunegridknn <- expand.grid(k = c(5,7,9,11,13,15,17))
modelKNN <- train(Volume ~ .,
                      method = "knn",
                      data = trainSet,
                      tuneGrid = tunegridknn,
                      trControl=fitControl,preProcess = c("center", "scale"))
print(modelKNN)

Testing Model

This phase helps us test our model to observe its performance on a new set of data.

#create a factor from the dummified data 
convertDummyToFactor <- function(dataframe){
  dataframe <- dataframe %>%
  mutate(
    
      ProductType = ifelse(ProductTypeLaptop == 1,'Laptop',
                       ifelse(ProductTypeNetbook == 1,'Netbook',
                          ifelse(ProductTypeSmartphone == 1,'Smartphone',
                             ifelse(ProductTypePC == 1,'PC',
                                    ifelse(ProductTypePrinter==1 , 'Printers',
                                     ifelse(ProductTypeAccessories ==1, 'Accessories',
                                        ifelse(ProductTypeExtendedWarranty == 1, 'Extended Warranty',
                                            ifelse(ProductTypeSoftware == 1, 'Software', "Others")))))))),
   
    
  .after = Volume
  )
  
  return(dataframe)
}



convertDummyToFactor2 <- function(dataframe){
  dataframe <- dataframe %>%
  mutate( ProductType = ifelse(ProductTypeLaptop == 1,'Laptop',
                       ifelse(ProductTypeNetbook == 1,'Netbook',
                          ifelse(ProductTypeSmartphone == 1,'Smartphone',
                             ifelse(ProductTypePC == 1,'PC',
                                    ifelse(ProductTypePrinter==1 , 'Printers',
                                     ifelse(ProductTypeAccessories ==1, 'Accessories',
                                        ifelse(ProductTypeExtendedWarranty == 1, 'Extended Warranty',
                                            ifelse(ProductTypeSoftware == 1, 'Software',
                                              ifelse(ProductTypeGameConsole == 1, 'Game Console',
                                                ifelse(ProductTypeDisplay == 1, 'Display',
                                                   ifelse(ProductTypePrinterSupplies == 1 , 'Printer Supplies',
                                                      ifelse(ProductTypePrinter == 1 , 'Printer',
                                                         ifelse(ProductTypeTablet == 1,'Tablet', 'Others'))))))))))))),
  .after = Volume
  )
  
  return(dataframe)
}

#convert dummy to factor
testSet <- convertDummyToFactor(testSet)

# a plot of the residual values against the independent variables
ggplot(testSet, aes(x=Volume,y=Errors, col=ProductType)) + geom_point() + geom_hline(yintercept=0 , linetype="dashed", color = "blue") +
ggtitle('Residual Plot of Volume')

INSIGHTS

  • we can see that the Netbook one of the products that was of concern to Blackwell was not in the test data set due to the size of the data.

  • The RMSE of the error between the predicted and actual is about plus or minus 380 a bit more than what we got during the training phase.

  • The predictor contribution or correlation of actual and predicted value is 80 percent

INSIGHTS

  • the distribution of the new Product volume shows that the majority of volume sold was between 0 to 500 unit and some few outliers in the thousands region.

  • we can see that for the Four Product types Laptop, Netbook, Smartphones, and PCs distribution with 4 star review shows a near perfect fit for all but smartphones. It also tells us that the more the volume the more the reviews

  • we can see that for the Four Product types Laptop, Netbook, Smartphones, and PCs distribution with 2 star review shows a near perfect fit for all but Laptop and Netbook It also tells us that the more the volume the more the reviews

  • we can see that for the Four Product types Laptop, Netbook, Smartphones, and PCs distribution with positive service review shows a near perfect fit for all. It also tells us that the more the volume the more the reviews

  • we can see that for the Four Product types Laptop, Netbook, Smartphones, and PCs distribution with Negative Service review shows a near perfect fit for all but smartphones and Netbook. It also tells us that the more the volume the more the reviews except for PC products which shows the more the volume the less the negative service reviews

  • the distribution of 4 star reviews and positive service review shows a perfect relationship between the two for all products so we can see that the higher the 4 star reviews (positive Customer reviews) the better the positive service review.

  • The distribution of the 2 star reviews and the negative service review shows us that the higher the count of 2 star reviews (negative customer reviews) the more the negative service review. There is an exception for Pc the less the 2 star Reviews the more the negative service review

Limitations

The following are the limitations of the analysis of the Blackwell new and existing Product data set

  • The major limitation is the lack of data to analyse. This has really limited the ranges of techniques that can be used for better analysis.

  • Incomplete data representation during modeling phase

  • Some key information were missing in the testing data set and could not be analyzed.

Conclusions

  • Form the analysis thus far we can observer that predicting the sales of some specific product type Laptop, smartphone, Netbooks, and PC can be done with a score of 94 percent accuracy and an error of 138 unit of volume sales. we could see the analysis of the mentioned products on the new product set.

  • The impact of customer reviews and service reviews are directly propotional and we could observe that the more 4 star ratings a product gets the more positive service reviews, likewise the more 2 star ratings or negative customer reviews the more negative service review. with an exception to PC that shows that the less negative customer review implies more negative service review.
